def: To blow together; to bring together; to collect;  to fusetogether; to join or weld; to consolidate.
To make lord or master; as, to impatronize one's self of aseigniory. [R.] Bacon.

To contend emulously; to seek or strive for the same thing,position, or reward for which another is striving; to contend inrivalry, as for a prize or in business; as, tradesmen compete withone another.The rival statesmen, with eyes fixed on America, were all the whilecompeting for European alliances. Bancroft.
Of or pert. to the Zuñis, or designating their linguisticstock. --n.
Pish! pooch! -- an exclamation used as an expression ofcontempt, disdain, dislike, etc. [Written also psha.]
Braided; broidered. [Obs.]Alle his clothes brouded up and down. Chaucer.

An opera in which the text and action are not interrupted byset arias, duets, etc., the music being determined throughout bydramatic appropriateness; musical drama of this character, ingeneral. It involves the use of a kind of melodious declamation, thedevelopment of leitmotif, great orchestral elaboration, and a fusionof poetry, music, action, and scene into an organic whole. The termis applied esp. to the later works of Wagner: "Tristan und Isolde,""Die Meistersinger," "Rheingold," "Walküre," "Siegfried,""Götterdämmerung," and "Parsifal."
Fit for, or capable of, marriage; of an age at which marriageis allowable.-- Mar"riage*a*ble*ness, n.
To divest of the office or authority of a magistrate. [Obs.]Milton.
A genus of birds including the bustards.
